      <h2>Commercial Cooler Types and Their Repair Needs</h2>
      <p><strong>Reach-In Coolers</strong></p>
      <p>Reach-in coolers are a staple in small to medium-sized commercial settings such as cafes, convenience stores, and
        delis. These coolers are designed for quick access and typically feature multiple shelves or compartments to organize
        various perishable items. Due to their frequent use, common repair needs include worn-out door gaskets, which can lead
        to air leakage and increased energy consumption. Additionally, the condenser and evaporator coils can become clogged
        with dust and debris, reducing the unit's efficiency. Basic repairs like gasket replacements usually cost around $100,
        while more complex issues such as coil cleaning or replacement can range from $200 to $500. Regular maintenance is
        essential to keep these coolers functioning optimally and to extend their lifespan.</p>
      <p><strong>Walk-In Coolers</strong></p>
      <p>Walk-in coolers are essential for larger commercial operations like restaurants, grocery stores, and food
        distribution centers. These units offer ample storage space and are built to handle a higher volume of goods. Common
        repair needs include issues with the refrigeration system, such as refrigerant leaks or compressor failures, and
        problems with the door seals and hinges, which can affect the cooler's efficiency. Repairs for refrigerant leaks can
        range from $300 to $800, depending on the extent of the leak and the type of refrigerant used. Compressor replacements
        are more costly, often ranging from $1,500 to $3,000. Regular inspections and maintenance, such as checking
        refrigerant levels and ensuring door seals are intact, are crucial to avoid these costly repairs.</p>
      <p><strong>Display Coolers</strong></p>
      <p>Display coolers are widely used in retail environments like supermarkets, bakeries, and beverage shops to showcase
        products while keeping them cool. These units are designed to be visually appealing and easily accessible to
        customers. Common repair issues include malfunctioning lighting systems, temperature control problems, and issues with
        the glass doors or panels, which can lead to condensation and reduced visibility. Light bulb or LED replacements are
        relatively inexpensive, typically costing between $50 and $200, while temperature control repairs can range from $200
        to $600. Glass door repairs or replacements can be more costly, ranging from $300 to $1,000. Regular cleaning and
        maintenance of both the interior and exterior components can help prolong the lifespan of display coolers.</p>
      <p><strong>Undercounter Coolers</strong></p>
      <p>Undercounter coolers are commonly found in bars, cafes, and small restaurants where space is at a premium. These
