      <h2><strong>What should I do if the door seal is damaged?</strong></h2>
      <p>A damaged door seal on your walk-in cooler or freezer can lead to temperature fluctuations, increased energy costs,
        and potential food spoilage. If you notice that the door seal is compromised, it’s essential to address the issue
        promptly. Here’s a step-by-step guide on what to do:</p>
      <p>1. <strong>Inspect the Damage</strong></p>
      <p>- <strong>Visual Inspection:</strong> Carefully examine the door seal to determine the extent of the damage. Look for
        cracks, tears, or areas where the seal is no longer tight.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Functional Test:</strong> Close the door and check for any gaps where cold air might be escaping. You can
        use a flashlight inside the cooler; if you see light coming through the seal from the outside, it’s damaged.</p>
      <p>2. <strong>Temporary Fixes</strong></p>
      <p>- <strong>Sealant or Tape:</strong> For minor damage, you can use a food-safe silicone sealant or high-quality tape
        as a temporary fix. This is not a long-term solution but can help maintain the cooler’s efficiency until a permanent
        repair is made.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Adjust Door Hinges:</strong> Sometimes, realigning the door can improve the seal’s effectiveness. Check if
        the door is properly aligned and adjust the hinges if needed.</p>
      <p>3. <strong>Clean the Seal and Surrounding Area</strong></p>
      <p>- <strong>Remove Debris:</strong> Clean the door seal and the area where it makes contact with the door frame. Dirt
        and debris can prevent a proper seal.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Sanitize:</strong> Use a food-safe cleaner to sanitize the seal and door frame. This helps in maintaining
        hygiene and ensures the new or repaired seal adheres properly.</p>
      <p>4. <strong>Order Replacement Parts</strong></p>
      <p>- <strong>Identify the Seal Type:</strong> Ensure you know the exact type and size of the door seal required for your
        walk-in cooler or freezer. This information is often available in the equipment’s manual or can be obtained from the
        manufacturer.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Purchase the Seal:</strong> Order the replacement door seal from a reputable supplier. Make sure it’s
        compatible with your specific model.</p>
      <p>5. <strong>Replace the Door Seal</strong></p>
      <p>- <strong>Remove the Old Seal:</strong> Carefully remove the damaged seal from the door. This may require unscrewing
        or unclipping it, depending on the design.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Install the New Seal:</strong> Attach the new door seal according to the manufacturer’s instructions.
        Ensure it fits snugly and securely around the entire door perimeter.</p>
      <p>- <strong>Test the Seal:</strong> Close the door and check for any gaps. Perform the flashlight test again to ensure
        no light passes through.</p>
      <p>6. <strong>Professional Assistance</strong></p>
      <p>- <strong>Expert Help:</strong> If you’re unsure about replacing the door seal yourself, or if the issue persists
        despite your efforts, it’s best to seek professional help. Same Day Appliance Repair specializes in commercial walk-in
